Dear Families,

     This week we began a new read-aloud: Mr. Popper=E2=80=99s Penguins.  K=
ids have
been interested in making predictions and talking about new vocabulary.  We
are more in the habit of pausing during reading to discuss plot points and
consider the motivations of the characters.  This week, Mr. Popper was
described as a =E2=80=9Cdreamer.=E2=80=9D We discussed what that might mean=
, and many kids
identified with that trait offering thoughts about how they like to
daydream, or often find themselves thinking or imagining throughout the
day.  So far, Mr. Popper has been dreaming of traveling and exploring
places around the world (specifically the Arctic and Antarctic), we are
waiting for those penguins to make an appearance.... Here is more about the
week:

Categorizing Shapes

     As we=E2=80=99ve been diving more into our unit on geometry, we=E2=80=
=99ve been
finding various ways in which shapes fit together and combinations of
shapes that make another shape.  On Wednesday, we worked as a class to
exhaust all possibilities to create a rhombus, trapezoid, and hexagon.

     On Friday, kids were sent off with their new math partners to create
geometry posters, categorizing shapes by their properties.  For example,
trapezoids, squares, rectangles, and rhombuses all have four (straight)
sides and four vertices. Some shapes were more puzzling that others; do
ovals and circles have sides?  As kids worked, they chatted about their
observations. Here are a few of their noticings:

