need more.=E2=80=9D

Keilee: =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s perfect!  It=E2=80=99s 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, n=
o wait, Otto, it=E2=80=99s 6
sides.  Hexagon!=E2=80=9D

Eleanor: =E2=80=9CColin picks one and I glue it.  We=E2=80=99re doing three=
 sides-
triangles.=E2=80=9D

Sebastian: =E2=80=9CLuka and me, we needed more space, so we=E2=80=99re put=
ting more
trapezoids on.=E2=80=9D



Work Time

     As we=E2=80=99ve wrapped up our animal dioramas, kids have sustained t=
heir
interest in working with clay (Model Magic).  This light-weight,
easy-to-mold, and quick-drying clay was perfect for creating our animals,
and kids have been exploring both representational and abstract sculpture.
We have trays full of snails, spirals, swirls, and people!

     Kids have also been working with rubber bands to create bracelets and
necklaces on the =E2=80=9Crainbow loom,=E2=80=9D a form of finger knitting.=
  In fact,
rainbow loom mania has practically taken over our classroom. Next week, we
are hoping to expand this interest and begin working on actual looms to
create woven potholders.



Book Baggies

    As our students are becoming more fluent readers, you may have noticed
the shift in the types of books or number of books your child is placing in
their book baggies. These new factors will influence how we continue to
bookshop.  If you=E2=80=99re child has 10-12 books in their baggies, please=
 don=E2=80=99t
feel rushed to read all the books in a week; take your time, enjoy the
books, and send them back when your family is ready to select new ones.

     Book shopping happens once a week, when children are ready to select
new books. If your child is taking home chapter books you can choose to
book shop every other week.  One way to incorporate more reading time into
your daily routines is by reading during your commutes. Have your child
pick one book to read during the commute to and from school, in no time
you=E2=80=99ll be done with all those books in the baggie.

     Along with reading during commutes, you can also encourage your
children to practice reading and writing the words on their rings. Each
ring is tailored to a child=E2=80=99s level and abilities, and these words =
will
help support them in their reading and writing.

     For children who are reading chapter books, we are encouraging book
discussions.  At school, children complete a =E2=80=9CStory Map,=E2=80=9D i=
dentifying the
problem, solution, beginning, middle, and end of a story.  At home, you
might check in with your child about similar topics, both as they read, and
when they complete, a book.



Have a great weekend,

Eleanor, Nita, and Shawna

